-- 
Oil Volatility Rises as Futures in Biggest 2-Day Drop Since May

-- B y   M a r g o t   H a b i b y
-- 
2011-04-12T19:31:05Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-12/oil-volatility-rises-as-futures-in-biggest-2-day-drop-since-may.html
Oil options volatility increased as
the underlying front-month futures tumbled in the biggest two-
day drop in almost 11 months.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
June, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a gauge
of options prices, was 31.6 percent as of 2 p.m. in  New York , up
from 30.2 percent yesterday.  Oil for May delivery dropped $3.67, or 3.3 percent, to
settle at $106.25 a barrel on the  New York Mercantile Exchange .
Prices have fallen 5.8 percent since reaching a 30-month high of
$112.79 on April 8, the biggest two-day retreat since May 14 and
17. Futures have risen 26 percent in the past year.  The most active contracts in electronic trading today were
May $105 puts with 6,488 lots changing hands. They gained 75
cents to 90 cents a barrel. May $110 calls, the next-most active
contract, fell $1.02 to 23 cents a barrel with 2,969 contracts
trading. One contract is for 1,000 barrels of oil.  May options expire on April 14.  Nymex distributes real-time data for electronic trading and
releases information on floor trading, where the bulk of options
trading occurs, the next business day.  May $110 puts were the most active options traded in the
previous session with 5,156 lots changing hands. They increased
73 cents to $1.33 a barrel. The next most active option, May
$105 puts, gained 6 cents to 15 cents a barrel on 4,966 lots.  Open interest was highest for December 2012 $80 puts with
40,208 contracts. Next were June $150 calls with 39,783 and
December $100 calls with 38,964.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Margot Habiby in  Dallas  at 
 mhabiby@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Dan Stets at   dstets@bloomberg.net . 